sentences: Jeanne Leleu (29 December 1898 – 11 March 1979) was a French pianist and composer.
With Geneviève Durony, Leleu gave the premiere performance of Ravel's Ma mère l'oye in 1910.
Ravel had composed his Prelude for a Paris Conservatoire sight-reading competition in 1913 and Leleu won the prize.
Her cantata Beatrix won the Prix de Rome in 1923.
In 1924 she took a position in the Villa Medicis in Rome, staying there for three years before returning to Paris.

After completing her studies, Leleu took a position as professor of sight reading at the Conservatoire and, in 1947, she was named professor of harmony.
She died in Paris at 80 years of age.
